Preclinical Study Report

Repeated Dose Toxicity Study by Intramuscular Administration of Vaccine in Rabbits
Study ID: RABBITV1 • SEND v3.1 • GLP (OECD) • Sponsor: BIOPHARMA, Inc.

1. Study Design & Demographics
Study Type: Repeat Dose Toxicity (GLP, OECD)
Species/Strain: New Zealand White Rabbit
Age at Start: 14 weeks
Total Animals: 60 (30M / 30F)
Route: Intramuscular (dorsal muscle, bilateral)
Dosing Frequency: Every 2 weeks
Dosing Duration: 37 days
Recovery Period: 4 weeks
Group 1 (Control): 0 mg/dose (Negative Control) – 20 animals
Group 2 (SENDVACC10): 12.5 mg/dose – 20 animals
Group 3 (SENDVACC99): 12.5 mg/dose – 20 animals
Sacrifice Plan (per group):
Terminal: 5M + 5F (end of treatment)
Recovery: 5M + 5F (after 4-week recovery)
Study Timeline: Study Start: 2018-08-03 | Males Dosing: 2018-08-20 → 2018-09-25 | Females Dosing: 2018-08-28 → 2018-09-25 | Terminal Sacrifice (M): 2018-09-19, (F): 2018-09-27 | Recovery Sacrifice (M): 2018-10-15, (F): 2018-10-23

Interpretation: Body weight gains were comparable across treatment groups for both sexes. No treatment-related effects on body weight were observed, indicating good tolerability at the systemic level. Both SENDVACC10 and SENDVACC99 treated animals maintained normal growth trajectories.
3. Food Consumption

Daily food consumption was measured individually for all animals throughout the study.

Interpretation: Food consumption patterns were similar across all treatment groups with no treatment-related decreases observed. Transient post-dosing fluctuations were minor and not considered biologically significant.
4. Body Temperature (Rectal)

Rectal temperature was measured as a vital sign parameter. Note: Temperature data was collected only for females in this dataset.

Interpretation: Rectal temperatures remained within the normal physiological range for rabbits (38.0-39.6°C) across all groups and timepoints. No pyrexic responses to vaccination were noted.

8. Immunogenicity – Antibody Response

H1-specific IgG antibody titers were measured by ELISA at multiple timepoints to assess immunogenicity of the vaccine candidates.

Key Finding: Both SENDVACC10 and SENDVACC99 elicited H1-specific IgG antibody responses, confirming immunogenicity of the vaccine candidates. Control animals showed minimal/no antibody response. Titers increased after initial dosing and were maintained or boosted after subsequent doses.

13. Conclusions & Overall Assessment
Overall Toxicological Assessment:
  • General Toxicity: No systemic toxicity was observed. Body weights, food consumption, and clinical observations were comparable across all groups throughout the study.
  • Local Tolerance: Injection site reactions (macroscopic red discoloration and microscopic inflammation) were observed in all groups including controls, consistent with the intramuscular route of administration. Treated groups showed expected vaccine-related local reactogenicity that was partially reversible after the recovery period.
  • Hematology & Clinical Chemistry: No treatment-related changes of toxicological significance were identified. Isolated statistically significant differences were within normal biological variability and lacked clear dose-response patterns.
  • Immunogenicity: Both SENDVACC10 and SENDVACC99 successfully elicited H1-specific IgG antibody responses, confirming the pharmacological activity of the vaccine candidates.
  • Organ Weights & Pathology: Immune-organ changes (lymph node and spleen germinal center hyperplasia) were consistent with expected immune activation following vaccination and are considered pharmacologically-related rather than adverse.
  • Reversibility: Findings observed at terminal sacrifice showed evidence of recovery or partial recovery in recovery sacrifice groups, supporting the reversible nature of vaccine-related effects.
NOAEL Determination: Based on the results of this study, the No Observed Adverse Effect Level (NOAEL) for both SENDVACC10 and SENDVACC99 was determined to be 12.5 mg/dose administered intramuscularly every 2 weeks in New Zealand White rabbits. All treatment-related findings were consistent with the intended pharmacological action (immune activation) and showed reversibility.
Analytical Methods: Descriptive statistics (mean, SD, SE) were calculated for continuous endpoints. One-way ANOVA was used for overall group comparisons, and Student's t-test for pairwise comparisons vs. control. Incidence tables are presented for pathology findings. Statistical analyses were performed using Python (scipy.stats). A significance level of α = 0.05 was used throughout, without multiplicity adjustment.
